window.TUSDATA=window.TUSDATA||{};
TUSDATA.statesProse=TUSDATA.statesProse||{};
Object.assign(TUSDATA.statesProse,{
"30":{origin:"Louisiana Purchase (1803) and Oregon Country (1846) → Montana Territory 1864 → statehood 1889",namedFor:"Spanish 'montaña' — mountain",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1862,text:"Blackfeet dominated the northern plains, Crow the Yellowstone country, Salish and Kootenai the valleys west of the Divide, with Assiniboine and Gros Ventre to the northeast. Horses arrived in the 1730s and transformed bison hunting. Lewis and Clark crossed in 1805-06; fur posts and Jesuit missions followed. The 1851 Fort Laramie treaty drew tribal boundaries on paper; the 1837 smallpox epidemic had already killed thousands of Blackfeet."},
  {from:1862,to:1889,text:"Gold at Bannack (1862), Virginia City (1863), and Last Chance Gulch (1864) drew thousands; Montana Territory organized in 1864 amid vigilante hangings. Lakota and Cheyenne fighters annihilated Custer at the Little Bighorn in 1876; the Nez Perce surrendered at Bear Paw in 1877. Hide hunters exterminated the bison by 1883, and starving tribes were confined to reservations. Butte copper boomed; statehood came in 1889."},
  {from:1889,to:1920,text:"Butte, 'the richest hill on earth,' supplied much of the world's copper as the Anaconda Company and its Copper Kings bought legislatures and newspapers; smelter smoke poisoned whole valleys. After the 1909 Enlarged Homestead Act, railroads lured tens of thousands of settlers to dry-land wheat claims on the eastern plains. Drought beginning in 1917 started the collapse."},
  {from:1920,to:2026,text:"The homestead bust emptied half of Montana's farms; hundreds of banks failed and tens of thousands left. Fort Peck Dam (1930s) was a New Deal colossus. Wheat, cattle, timber, and oil carried the postwar decades; Butte's mining legacy is the toxic Berkeley Pit. The 1972 constitution guarantees a 'clean and healthful environment.' Tourism and booming Bozeman now coexist with seven reservations and shrinking rural counties."}
 ],
 sources:["Montana Historical Society","U.S. Census Bureau","Library of Congress"]},
"31":{origin:"Louisiana Purchase (1803) → Nebraska Territory 1854 (Kansas-Nebraska Act) → statehood 1867",namedFor:"From the Otoe and Omaha words for 'flat water' — the Platte River",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1854,text:"The Pawnee farmed corn and hunted bison along the Platte and Loup; Omaha, Otoe-Missouria, and Ponca villages lined the Missouri; Lakota power grew in the west. Spain and France claimed the region before the 1803 Louisiana Purchase. Steamboats, fur posts like Bellevue, and 1840s Oregon-California-Mormon trail wagons followed the Platte valley road; cholera and smallpox traveled with them."},
  {from:1854,to:1890,text:"The 1854 Kansas-Nebraska Act organized Nebraska Territory and repealed the Missouri Compromise, igniting national crisis. Daniel Freeman filed the nation's first Homestead Act claim near Beatrice on January 1, 1863. The Union Pacific built west from Omaha; statehood came in 1867. The Pawnee, decimated by disease and Lakota raids, ceded everything and moved to Indian Territory by 1875; the Ponca's forced 1877 removal led to Standing Bear's landmark 1879 personhood ruling."},
  {from:1890,to:1945,text:"Drought and the 1890s depression fueled Populism — the party wrote its 1892 platform in Omaha, and William Jennings Bryan carried its banner. German, Czech, Scandinavian, and German-Russian farmers turned grassland to corn and wheat. Omaha's stockyards ranked among the world's largest; in 1919 a mob lynched Will Brown at its courthouse. George Norris won rural electrification and the nation's only unicameral legislature (1937)."},
  {from:1945,to:2026,text:"Center-pivot irrigation, a Nebraska invention, drew the Ogallala Aquifer to water millions of acres, making the state a corn, beef, and ethanol power while straining groundwater. Strategic Air Command headquartered at Offutt Air Force Base near Omaha, which grew into an insurance and finance center anchored by Berkshire Hathaway. Rural counties keep emptying as Omaha and Lincoln, increasingly diverse, hold most Nebraskans."}
 ],
 sources:["History Nebraska","U.S. Census Bureau"]},
"32":{origin:"Mexican Cession (1848) → Utah Territory 1850 → Nevada Territory 1861 → statehood 1864",namedFor:"Spanish 'nevada' — snow-covered, from the Sierra Nevada",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1848,text:"Western Shoshone, Northern and Southern Paiute, and Washoe peoples lived skillfully in the Great Basin's scarcity — piñon harvests, rabbit drives, marsh villages. Spain claimed the region largely unseen; Mexico inherited it in 1821. Fur trappers like Ogden and Walker, then Frémont's expeditions, mapped the rivers in the 1820s-40s, and the 1848 Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo transferred the Basin to the United States."},
  {from:1848,to:1864,text:"Mormon Station (1851) and mail routes preceded the 1859 Comstock Lode, whose silver built Virginia City and San Francisco fortunes. Miners overran Paiute lands; the 1860 Pyramid Lake War killed dozens, and piñon groves fell for mine timbers. The 1863 Ruby Valley Treaty promised passage through Western Shoshone lands never formally ceded. Lincoln, needing votes, rushed 'Battle Born' Nevada to statehood on October 31, 1864."},
  {from:1864,to:1931,text:"Comstock silver peaked in the 1870s and collapsed; Nevada nearly depopulated until the Tonopah and Goldfield strikes of the 1900s. Newlands Reclamation projects diverted Paiute water from Pyramid Lake. Quick divorces and prizefights hinted at a coming formula: in 1931, amid Depression, Nevada legalized casino gambling as Hoover Dam construction began, creating Boulder City and feeding Las Vegas."},
  {from:1931,to:2026,text:"Federal money remade the desert: Hoover Dam power, wartime magnesium, and from 1951 the Nevada Test Site, where roughly a thousand nuclear tests sickened downwinders. Las Vegas grew from mob-financed Strip to corporate resort capital. Nevada leads US gold production; Reno draws tech and logistics. Western Shoshone land claims, pressed by the Dann sisters, persist, and Colorado River shortages shadow one of the most urbanized states."}
 ],
 sources:["Nevada Historical Society","U.S. Census Bureau","National Archives"]},
"33":{origin:"English colony (1623; royal province 1679) → independent state 1776 → ratified Constitution 1788 (9th, putting it into effect)",namedFor:"Named in 1629 by John Mason for Hampshire, England",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1788,text:"Abenaki peoples — Pennacook and western bands — had been devastated by epidemics and colonial wars; most withdrew north to Odanak in Quebec, though families remained quietly. Portsmouth merchants grew rich on timber, and the Crown reserved tall white pines for Royal Navy masts, breeding resentment. New Hampshire ousted royal government early, adopted the first state constitution in January 1776, and its June 1788 ratification — the ninth — put the US Constitution into effect."},
  {from:1788,to:1920,text:"Concord became the capital in 1808; Dartmouth College v. Woodward (1819) shaped American corporate law. Water-powered textile mills rose on the Merrimack — Manchester's Amoskeag became one of the world's largest cotton-mill complexes, run on French-Canadian, Irish, and Greek immigrant labor. Granite quarrying named the state; hill farms emptied westward. Logging stripped the White Mountains until the 1911 Weeks Act launched eastern national forests; Portsmouth hosted the 1905 Russo-Japanese peace treaty."},
  {from:1920,to:2026,text:"The presidential primary, first held in 1916 and leading the nation's calendar since 1920, made New Hampshire a political proving ground. Amoskeag closed in 1935; defense electronics and Boston-commuter growth replaced textiles in the south. The state built an identity on no general income or sales tax and the 1945 motto 'Live Free or Die.' The Old Man of the Mountain collapsed in 2003; tourism and tech sustain an aging population."}
 ],
 sources:["New Hampshire Historical Society","Library of Congress"]},
"34":{origin:"Lenape homeland → Dutch New Netherland → English colony 1664 → ratified Constitution 1787 (3rd state)",namedFor:"For the Channel Island of Jersey, home of proprietor Sir George Carteret",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1787,text:"Lenape communities, reduced by disease and land fraud to a fraction of their people, ceded remaining claims at the 1758 Treaty of Easton; Brotherton in the Pine Barrens became one of the first Indian reservations, its residents departing for New York by 1802. Farms fed Philadelphia and New York. The Revolution's crossroads ran through Trenton, Princeton, and Monmouth; New Jersey ratified the Constitution third, in December 1787."},
  {from:1787,to:1870,text:"New Jersey's 1776 constitution let property-holding women vote until 1807 — then took it back. Hamilton's Society for Establishing Useful Manufactures founded Paterson (1791), harnessing the Great Falls for what became Silk City. Canals and the Camden and Amboy Railroad knit the New York-Philadelphia corridor. Slavery died slowly under an 1804 gradual abolition law; a handful of people remained bound as 'apprentices' until 1865."},
  {from:1870,to:1945,text:"Edison's Menlo Park and West Orange labs produced the phonograph and practical electric light. Refineries, chemical works, and ports industrialized the north; immigrants landed at Ellis Island, most of which courts later ruled lies in New Jersey. Trenton wore the slogan 'Trenton Makes, the World Takes'; Paterson's silk workers struck in 1913. Shipyards and Fort Dix powered two world wars; Einstein settled at Princeton's Institute for Advanced Study."},
  {from:1945,to:2026,text:"The Turnpike and Parkway (1950s) plus GI mortgages built vast suburbs; redlining segregated them. Newark's 1967 uprising marked urban disinvestment. Pharmaceutical giants earned the nickname 'the nation's medicine chest'; container shipping, pioneered at Port Newark, globalized trade. Hurricane Sandy battered the shore in 2012. Now the densest and among the most diverse states, New Jersey rides pharma, ports, and proximity to two great cities."}
 ],
 sources:["New Jersey Historical Society","U.S. Census Bureau","Encyclopaedia Britannica"]},
"35":{origin:"Spanish New Mexico (1598) → Mexico 1821 → Mexican Cession 1848 → New Mexico Territory 1850 → statehood 1912",namedFor:"Spanish 'Nuevo México' (1560s), named by explorers hoping for another Mexico — the name predates the nation of Mexico",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1821,text:"Pueblo nations from Taos to Zuni held their villages under a Spanish rule reshaped by their 1680 Revolt, which expelled Spain for twelve years and won lasting accommodation: Pueblo lands and religion endured alongside Catholicism. Santa Fe (1610) anchored a poor, isolated province of Hispanic villages and genízaro settlements bound by raiding and trading with Comanche, Apache, Navajo, and Ute neighbors; a 1786 Comanche peace steadied the frontier."},
  {from:1821,to:1848,text:"Mexican independence in 1821 opened the Santa Fe Trail, tying New Mexico to the US economy through Missouri wagon trade. Land grants expanded ranching; Navajo and Apache raiding, and slave-taking in both directions, continued. In 1846 Kearny's Army of the West occupied Santa Fe without a battle; the 1847 Taos Revolt was crushed, and the 1848 Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo ceded New Mexico, nominally protecting Hispanic land titles."},
  {from:1848,to:1912,text:"The Compromise of 1850 made New Mexico a territory. The Army waged relentless campaigns: Carson's scorched-earth drive forced more than 8,000 Navajos on the 1864 Long Walk to Bosque Redondo, where roughly a quarter died before the 1868 treaty allowed return; Apache resistance lasted until Geronimo's 1886 surrender. Railroads arrived in 1879; courts and the Santa Fe Ring stripped many Hispanic land grants. Statehood finally came on January 6, 1912."},
  {from:1912,to:2026,text:"The Manhattan Project built secret Los Alamos; the first atomic bomb exploded at Trinity Site on July 16, 1945, its downwind villages uncompensated for decades. National labs, White Sands, and Permian Basin oil drive the economy alongside chronic poverty; uranium mining left cancer across the Navajo Nation. Majority-minority, home to 23 tribes and pueblos, New Mexico sustains a layered Indigenous-Hispanic-Anglo identity."}
 ],
 sources:["New Mexico History Museum","National Park Service","U.S. Census Bureau"]},
"36":{origin:"Dutch New Netherland 1624 → English New York 1664 → independent state 1776 → ratified Constitution 1788 (11th)",namedFor:"For the Duke of York, later James II, after the English seizure of New Netherland in 1664",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1788,text:"The Haudenosaunee Confederacy — Mohawk, Oneida, Onondaga, Cayuga, Seneca, Tuscarora — dominated diplomacy between empires through the Covenant Chain at Albany. The Revolution split the Six Nations; Washington ordered the 1779 Sullivan-Clinton campaign, which burned some forty Seneca and Cayuga towns and their harvests. Postwar treaties and coerced state purchases confined the Haudenosaunee to small reservations as Loyalist Mohawks followed Brant to Canada. New York ratified the Constitution eleventh, in July 1788."},
  {from:1788,to:1825,text:"Land companies auctioned Iroquois country to Yankee settlers; the 1794 Treaty of Canandaigua, still commemorated, guaranteed remaining Seneca lands. New York City, briefly the national capital, became the largest US city by 1810. DeWitt Clinton's Erie Canal (1817-1825) cut freight costs by over ninety percent, funneling Great Lakes grain through Buffalo to Manhattan and making New York the Empire State."},
  {from:1825,to:1901,text:"Canal country bred ferment: revivalism, Mormonism's birth, abolitionism, and the 1848 Seneca Falls women's rights convention. Waves of Irish and German, then Jewish and Italian immigrants landed at Castle Garden and, from 1892, Ellis Island; the Statue of Liberty rose in 1886. Tammany Hall perfected machine politics. Upstate factories — Rochester optics, Schenectady electricity — and Wall Street finance made New York the nation's economic engine."},
  {from:1901,to:2026,text:"Skyscrapers, the subway (1904), the Harlem Renaissance, and Broadway defined the metropolis; the 1911 Triangle fire reshaped labor law. Robert Moses rebuilt — and bulldozed — neighborhoods; the Kinzua Dam (1965) flooded Seneca treaty land. Deindustrialization hollowed upstate cities; New York City skirted bankruptcy in 1975, absorbed the September 11, 2001 attacks, and rebounded on finance, media, and tech. More than one in five New Yorkers today is foreign-born."}
 ],
 sources:["New York State Museum","Library of Congress","U.S. Census Bureau"]},
"37":{origin:"Carolina charter 1663 → royal colony 1729 → independence 1776 → ratified Constitution 1789 (12th)",namedFor:"Carolina, from Latin Carolus — honoring King Charles I",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1789,text:"Cherokee towns held the mountains; the Catawba survived through alliance; the Tuscarora, shattered in the 1711-13 war, had gone north to join the Haudenosaunee. Naval stores from longleaf pine — tar and pitch — plus tobacco and enslaved labor drove the colony. Backcountry Regulators rose against corrupt officials, crushed at Alamance (1771). The 1776 Halifax Resolves first authorized a vote for independence; ratification came twelfth, in 1789, once a Bill of Rights was assured."},
  {from:1789,to:1865,text:"A slave society hardened: cotton and tobacco plantations east, yeoman farms west. Gold found at Reed's farm in 1799 made North Carolina the leading US producer until California. In 1838 federal troops drove most Cherokees west on the Trail of Tears; those who stayed became the Eastern Band at Qualla Boundary. Seceding reluctantly in May 1861, the state lost more soldiers than any other Confederate state; Bennett Place saw the war's largest surrender."},
  {from:1865,to:1960,text:"A biracial Fusion coalition won power in the 1890s — answered by the 1898 Wilmington coup, when white supremacists overthrew the elected government and killed Black citizens, then a 1900 disfranchisement amendment. Duke's tobacco empire, Piedmont textiles, and High Point furniture industrialized the state while sharecropping bound the east. The Wright brothers flew at Kitty Hawk in 1903. Black North Carolinians left in the Great Migration."},
  {from:1960,to:2026,text:"Greensboro's February 1960 sit-ins ignited a national movement. Research Triangle Park (opened 1959) drew IBM and biotech, remaking Raleigh-Durham; Charlotte became the nation's second-largest banking center. Textiles and furniture fled overseas after NAFTA. Hurricanes Floyd, Matthew, Florence, and Helene (2024) hammered east and west alike. The Lumbee, the largest tribe east of the Mississippi, still seek full federal recognition."}
 ],
 sources:["North Carolina Office of Archives and History","U.S. Census Bureau"]},
"38":{origin:"Louisiana Purchase (1803) → Dakota Territory 1861 → statehood 1889 (39th)",namedFor:"Dakota — 'friend' or 'ally,' the Dakota people's own name",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1862,text:"Mandan, Hidatsa, and Arikara earth-lodge towns on the Missouri were the northern plains' great trade hubs; Lewis and Clark wintered among them in 1804-05, meeting Sakakawea. Dakota and Lakota bands, with Ojibwe and Métis in the Red River country, hunted bison. The 1837 steamboat-borne smallpox epidemic nearly annihilated the Mandan — from over a thousand people to little more than a hundred — and the three tribes later merged at Like-a-Fishhook Village."},
  {from:1862,to:1889,text:"After the 1862 US-Dakota War in Minnesota, punitive expeditions struck camps at Whitestone Hill (1863) and Killdeer Mountain (1864), killing noncombatants. Fort Berthold and Standing Rock reservations were repeatedly carved down. The Northern Pacific and Red River Valley bonanza farms — wheat operations of thousands of acres — advertised Dakota to Norwegian and German-Russian homesteaders. The 1889 Omnibus Bill split Dakota Territory; North Dakota became the 39th state."},
  {from:1889,to:1953,text:"Wheat monoculture bound farmers to distant railroads, banks, and Minneapolis millers; fury at them built the Nonpartisan League, which captured state government by 1919 and founded the still-operating Bank of North Dakota and State Mill. Drought and Depression emptied farms in the 1930s. The 1944 Pick-Sloan Plan authorized Missouri River dams aimed at tribal bottomlands — chairman George Gillette wept signing the 1948 cession."},
  {from:1953,to:2026,text:"Garrison Dam (closed 1953) drowned over 150,000 acres of Fort Berthold's best land, displacing most Three Affiliated Tribes families. Cold War missile fields spread across the prairie; agriculture consolidated as rural counties emptied. Bakken shale fracking after 2006 made North Dakota the second-largest oil-producing state, swelling boomtowns like Williston. In 2016-17, Standing Rock's resistance to the Dakota Access Pipeline drew thousands of water protectors."}
 ],
 sources:["State Historical Society of North Dakota","U.S. Census Bureau"]},
"39":{origin:"Ohio Country ceded by Britain 1783 → Northwest Territory 1787 → statehood 1803 (17th)",namedFor:"From the Seneca 'Ohi:yo' — good or great river",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1795,text:"The Ohio Country — home of Shawnee, Miami, Wyandot, Delaware, Ottawa, and Mingo peoples — was the continent's flashpoint: the French and Indian War began over it; Pontiac's War swept it in 1763. The 1787 Northwest Ordinance promised statehood and banned slavery. A Native confederacy destroyed St. Clair's army in 1791, the worst-ever Native victory over the US army, before Fallen Timbers (1794) and the Treaty of Greenville (1795) took most of Ohio."},
  {from:1795,to:1850,text:"Settlers poured down the Ohio River; statehood came in 1803 with Chillicothe the first capital. Tecumseh's confederacy failed in the War of 1812; piecemeal cessions followed until the Wyandot, the last tribal nation in Ohio, left Upper Sandusky in 1843. Canals from 1825 and the National Road made Cincinnati 'Porkopolis'; Oberlin admitted Black students and women, and Underground Railroad routes crossed the state."},
  {from:1850,to:1969,text:"Ohio industrialized massively: Rockefeller's Standard Oil in Cleveland, Akron rubber, Youngstown steel, Dayton invention — cash registers and the Wright brothers. It sent Grant, Sherman, and Sheridan to war and seven Ohio-born presidents to the White House. European immigrants and the Great Migration manned the mills. By the 1960s Lake Erie was declared dying, and in June 1969 the oily Cuyahoga River caught fire, galvanizing environmentalism."},
  {from:1969,to:2026,text:"The Cuyahoga fire helped spur the EPA and Clean Water Act; Kent State's May 1970 shootings shook the nation. Steel collapsed after the 1970s — Youngstown's mills closed and 'Rust Belt' entered the language. Healthcare (Cleveland Clinic), finance, and logistics partly replaced them; Intel began building a huge semiconductor complex near Columbus in 2022. Once the ultimate bellwether, Ohio now leans Republican."}
 ],
 sources:["Ohio History Connection","National Archives","U.S. Census Bureau"]},
"40":{origin:"Louisiana Purchase (1803) → Indian Territory (1830s) + Oklahoma Territory (1890) → merged at statehood 1907",namedFor:"Choctaw 'okla humma' — red people — coined by Choctaw chief Allen Wright in 1866",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1830,text:"Caddo and Wichita farming towns held the river valleys, Osage hunters ranged the northeast, and Comanche and Kiowa power ruled the western plains at the edge of Comanchería. France traded, Spain claimed, and the 1803 Louisiana Purchase transferred paper title. The US then began designating the region for removal: 1820s treaties pushed Choctaw and Cherokee claims onto lands already occupied, igniting Osage-Cherokee warfare."},
  {from:1830,to:1866,text:"The 1830 Indian Removal Act made this 'Indian Territory.' The Five Tribes — Cherokee, Choctaw, Chickasaw, Muscogee, Seminole — were marched from the Southeast in the 1830s; thousands died on the Trail of Tears, roughly 4,000 Cherokees alone. The nations rebuilt with written constitutions, courts, newspapers, schools — and plantation slavery. The Civil War split them, and the punitive 1866 Reconstruction treaties seized the territory's western half and mandated citizenship for freedpeople."},
  {from:1866,to:1907,text:"Railroads and cattle trails crossed; the 1867 Medicine Lodge treaties confined the Plains tribes, and the 1874-75 Red River War crushed Comanche and Kiowa resistance. After Boomer agitation, the April 22, 1889 land run filled the Unassigned Lands overnight; Oklahoma Territory followed in 1890. The Dawes and Curtis Acts dissolved tribal governments and allotted communal lands, shedding millions of 'surplus' acres. The Sequoyah statehood bid failed; the twin territories merged as Oklahoma in 1907."},
  {from:1907,to:1945,text:"Oil gushers at Glenn Pool, Cushing, and Seminole made Tulsa the 'Oil Capital of the World' and made Osage headright holders, for a time, the world's richest people per capita — until the 1920s 'Reign of Terror' murders. On May 31-June 1, 1921, a white mob destroyed Tulsa's prosperous Greenwood district, killing as many as 300 Black residents. Dust Bowl storms then drove hundreds of thousands of 'Okies' down Route 66."},
  {from:1945,to:2026,text:"Aviation at Tinker Air Force Base, oil and gas, wheat, and cattle anchor the economy; Oklahoma City rebuilt after the 1995 bombing killed 168. Thirty-nine tribal nations headquartered in the state became major governments and employers. McGirt v. Oklahoma (2020) held that much of eastern Oklahoma remains reservation land for federal criminal law, and Tulsa began a formal reckoning with the 1921 massacre."}
 ],
 sources:["Oklahoma Historical Society","National Archives","U.S. Census Bureau"]},
"41":{origin:"Oregon Country (US by 1846 treaty) → Oregon Territory 1848 → statehood 1859",namedFor:"Disputed origin; possibly from 'Ouaricon,' a French mapmaker's error for a river flowing west",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1843,text:"Chinookan towns ran the Columbia River trade; Kalapuyans burned and tended the Willamette Valley; Nez Perce, Cayuse, and Umatilla held the plateau; dense nations lined the coast. Maritime traders brought smallpox by the 1780s, and the malaria epidemics of 1830-33 killed as many as nine in ten lower-Columbia and valley people. Astoria (1811) and Hudson's Bay Company's Fort Vancouver anchored the fur trade under US-British joint occupation."},
  {from:1843,to:1859,text:"Wagon trains rolled over the Oregon Trail from 1843; the 1846 treaty fixed the 49th-parallel border. The 1850 Donation Land Act granted settlers free claims on land never ceded. The 1847 Whitman killings sparked the Cayuse War, and Rogue Valley gold-rush violence ended with tribes force-marched to the Coast and Grand Ronde reservations in 1856. Oregon entered the Union in 1859 with a constitution barring Black residents, the only state admitted with one."},
  {from:1859,to:1945,text:"The Modoc War (1872-73) and the Nez Perce flight of 1877 closed armed resistance; boarding schools like Chemawa targeted the next generation. Railroads, wheat, salmon canneries, and above all timber — Oregon became the top lumber state — built Portland. The Klan briefly dominated 1920s politics. New Deal dams began remaking the Columbia; Kaiser's wartime shipyards drew Black workers to Vanport, destroyed by a 1948 flood."},
  {from:1945,to:2026,text:"Plywood boomed; 1954 termination policy hit western Oregon tribes and the Klamath, restored between 1977 and 1986. Tektronix seeded the Silicon Forest, Intel became the largest employer, and Nike rose from Eugene track. The 1990s spotted-owl injunctions slashed federal logging, remaking timber towns. Portland's growth boundary, wine country, and outdoor identity now coexist with wildfire smoke, homelessness, and nine federally recognized tribes rebuilding."}
 ],
 sources:["Oregon Historical Society","U.S. Census Bureau"]},
"42":{origin:"Penn's proprietary charter 1681 → independence 1776 → ratified Constitution 1787 (2nd state)",namedFor:"'Penn's woods' — Latin sylvania, honoring Admiral William Penn, father of founder William Penn",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1787,text:"Penn's 'peaceable kingdom' was already broken: the 1737 Walking Purchase defrauded the Lenape, who moved west with Shawnees into the Ohio Country. The French and Indian War bloodied the frontier after Braddock's 1755 defeat; the Paxton Boys massacred peaceful Conestoga people in 1763. Philadelphia, the colonies' largest city, hosted the Declaration and the Constitutional Convention; Pennsylvania ratified second in December 1787, and its 1780 gradual abolition act was America's first."},
  {from:1787,to:1859,text:"The Whiskey Rebellion (1794) tested federal power while Philadelphia served as national capital through 1800. Anthracite coal fired iron furnaces; canals and then the Pennsylvania Railroad — for decades the world's largest corporation — crossed the mountains on Irish and German immigrant labor. In 1859 Edwin Drake struck oil at Titusville, launching the modern petroleum industry."},
  {from:1859,to:1945,text:"Gettysburg (July 1863) turned the Civil War. Carnegie's Pittsburgh steel and the anthracite country powered industrial America at brutal cost: the 1889 Johnstown Flood killed 2,209; the Homestead strike (1892) and the 1902 anthracite strike defined labor war; children worked the coal breakers. Eastern and southern European immigrants and Black Southerners of the Great Migration manned the mills through two world wars."},
  {from:1945,to:2026,text:"Steel and coal collapsed in the 1970s-80s; Pittsburgh lost half its population and reinvented itself around universities, medicine, and robotics. Three Mile Island's 1979 partial meltdown near Harrisburg froze US nuclear construction for a generation. Marcellus Shale fracking after 2008 made Pennsylvania the second-largest natural gas producer. Philadelphia anchors an eds-and-meds economy, and the state remains a decisive presidential battleground."}
 ],
 sources:["Pennsylvania Historical and Museum Commission","Library of Congress"]},
"44":{origin:"Williams's settlement 1636; royal charter 1663 → independence 1776 → ratified Constitution 1790 (13th, last of the original states)",namedFor:"Uncertain — Verrazzano's comparison to the isle of Rhodes, or Dutch 'Roodt Eylandt,' red island",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1790,text:"The Narragansett, the region's former power, had been broken in King Philip's War — the 1675 Great Swamp Massacre killed hundreds — and survivors held a shrinking Charlestown reservation. Newport thrived as a hub of the African slave trade; Rhode Islanders financed roughly a thousand slaving voyages. Colonists burned the revenue schooner Gaspee in 1772, renounced allegiance in May 1776, then held out until May 1790 as the last original state to ratify the Constitution."},
  {from:1790,to:1860,text:"Slater Mill at Pawtucket (1793) spun America's first successful water-powered cotton yarn, igniting the Industrial Revolution; Blackstone Valley mills, worked by families and children, spun slave-grown cotton. Providence's Brown family split famously over the slave trade. By the 1840s most workingmen — many Irish Catholic — could not vote; Thomas Dorr's 1842 rebellion won only a grudging, nativist-tinged expansion of suffrage."},
  {from:1860,to:1945,text:"Textiles, woolens, machine tools, and Gorham silver made Providence an industrial giant — the self-styled jewelry capital of the world — drawing French Canadian, Italian, Portuguese, and Cape Verdean workers. The state unilaterally 'detribalized' the Narragansett in 1880 and sold their land. Newport became the Gilded Age resort and a Navy town. Mills fled south after the 1934 national textile strike; the 1938 hurricane devastated the coast."},
  {from:1945,to:2026,text:"Textile flight left mill towns poor, and jewelry manufacturing faded by the 1980s. The Navy remains a pillar — the Naval War College and undersea warfare research. The Narragansett won federal recognition in 1983. Education and medicine, from Brown and RISD to hospital systems, anchor Providence's revival. America's first offshore wind farm spun up off Block Island in 2016; the smallest state bets on the blue economy."}
 ],
 sources:["Rhode Island Historical Society","U.S. Census Bureau"]},
"45":{origin:"Carolina charter 1663 → royal colony 1729 → independence 1776 → ratified Constitution 1788 (8th)",namedFor:"Carolina, from Latin Carolus — honoring King Charles I",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1788,text:"Rice and indigo, grown in engineered swamp fields by enslaved Africans whose knowledge made them possible, created North America's richest — and Black-majority — colony; Gullah Geechee culture took root. The Cherokee lost towns and land in the 1760-61 war; the Catawba survived on a small reservation. Charleston was the continent's largest slave port. Partisan warfare raged through the Revolution — Kings Mountain, Cowpens; South Carolina ratified the Constitution eighth, in May 1788."},
  {from:1788,to:1865,text:"Cotton and the domestic slave trade enriched planters who led national proslavery politics: the 1822 Vesey conspiracy brought savage reprisal, and Calhoun's nullification crisis of 1832-33 rehearsed disunion. South Carolina seceded first, on December 20, 1860; the war began at Fort Sumter on April 12, 1861. Sherman's army burned Columbia in 1865, and the enslaved majority — 57 percent of the population — claimed freedom."},
  {from:1865,to:1948,text:"Reconstruction seated Black majorities in the legislature until Red Shirt terror — the 1876 Hamburg Massacre among it — 'redeemed' the state; the 1895 constitution disfranchised Black Carolinians. Sharecropping, phosphate mining, and whites-only upstate cotton mills defined a poor economy; the boll weevil and the Great Migration emptied the fields. In the late 1940s, Judge Waties Waring's rulings began cracking the white primary."},
  {from:1948,to:2026,text:"Briggs v. Elliott, from Clarendon County, became part of Brown v. Board of Education. Desegregation came grudgingly; in 1968 state troopers killed three students at Orangeburg. BMW (1994), Michelin, Boeing, and the port of Charleston built a manufacturing corridor. After a white supremacist murdered nine worshippers at Charleston's Emanuel AME Church in 2015, the Confederate flag finally left the State House grounds."}
 ],
 sources:["South Carolina Department of Archives and History","Library of Congress"]},
"46":{origin:"Louisiana Purchase (1803) → Dakota Territory 1861 → statehood 1889 (40th)",namedFor:"Dakota — 'friend' or 'ally,' the Dakota people's own name",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1868,text:"The Oceti Sakowin — Lakota, Dakota, Nakota — moved west with the horse; Lakota bands took the Black Hills, sacred Paha Sapa, around 1776 and dominated the northern plains as smallpox shattered the riverine Arikara. Lewis and Clark passed in 1804; fur posts like Fort Pierre followed. The 1851 and 1868 Fort Laramie treaties recognized vast Lakota territory — the Great Sioux Reservation, including the Black Hills, forever."},
  {from:1868,to:1890,text:"Custer's 1874 expedition announced gold, and miners swarmed illegally into Deadwood. After Little Bighorn, Congress's 1877 'sell or starve' act seized the Black Hills — a taking the Lakota never accepted. Railroads and homesteaders claimed the east; the 1889 agreement broke the Great Sioux Reservation into six pieces, and South Dakota became a state. On December 29, 1890, the Seventh Cavalry massacred some 250-300 Lakota at Wounded Knee."},
  {from:1890,to:1973,text:"Homesteaders broke the west-river sod, and drought broke many of them; Depression dust emptied counties. Mount Rushmore was blasted into the sacred Hills (1927-41) while the Homestake mine dug gold for over a century. Pick-Sloan dams like Oahe flooded some 200,000 acres of Missouri River reservation bottomland. In 1973, American Indian Movement activists occupied Wounded Knee for 71 days in a siege watched worldwide."},
  {from:1973,to:2026,text:"In 1980 the Supreme Court ruled the Black Hills taking unlawful; the Lakota refuse the compensation — now over a billion dollars in trust — and demand land back. Citibank moved its card operations to Sioux Falls in 1981 after usury caps fell; finance, health systems, agriculture, and Rushmore-Sturgis tourism drive the economy. Pine Ridge and other reservations endure some of America's deepest poverty amid strong cultural revival."}
 ],
 sources:["South Dakota State Historical Society","National Archives","U.S. Census Bureau"]},
"47":{origin:"North Carolina's western lands, ceded 1790 → Southwest Territory → statehood 1796 (16th)",namedFor:"From Tanasi, a Cherokee town on the Little Tennessee River",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1796,text:"The Cherokee held the eastern valleys and the Chickasaw the west when Anglo settlers crossed illegally into the Watauga country in the 1770s. The 1775 Transylvania Purchase and relentless encroachment brought war; Dragging Canoe's Chickamauga Cherokee resisted until 1794. The failed State of Franklin (1784-88) gave way to the Southwest Territory, and Tennessee — the first state carved from federal territory — entered the Union on June 1, 1796."},
  {from:1796,to:1861,text:"Andrew Jackson's rise ran through Tennessee land speculation and the 1818 Chickasaw cession that opened West Tennessee to cotton and slavery. His 1830 Removal Act culminated in 1838, when US soldiers herded Cherokees into stockades and onto the Trail of Tears; roughly 4,000 died. Memphis boomed on cotton and the slave trade, while East Tennessee's small farms held few slaves, seeding wartime Unionism."},
  {from:1861,to:1933,text:"Tennessee seceded last, in June 1861, and hosted more battles than any state but Virginia — Shiloh, Stones River, Franklin, Nashville. The Klan was founded at Pulaski in 1865; the 1866 Memphis Massacre killed dozens of Black residents. Yellow fever gutted Memphis in 1878. Beale Street bred the blues, the Grand Ole Opry began broadcasting in 1925, and the Scopes trial that year put evolution on trial in Dayton."},
  {from:1933,to:2026,text:"The Tennessee Valley Authority (1933) dammed the rivers, electrified farms, and displaced thousands; secret Oak Ridge enriched uranium for the Hiroshima bomb. Nashville's 1960 student sit-ins desegregated downtown lunch counters; Dr. King was assassinated at Memphis's Lorraine Motel on April 4, 1968. Country music, healthcare corporations, FedEx, and auto plants now power a fast-growing, no-income-tax state."}
 ],
 sources:["Tennessee State Library and Archives","Library of Congress"]},
"48":{origin:"Spanish Texas → Mexican Texas 1821 → Republic of Texas 1836 → annexed to the Union 1845",namedFor:"Caddo 'táysha' — friend or ally — rendered by the Spanish as Tejas",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1821,text:"Comanchería ruled: mounted Comanches with Kiowa allies controlled the plains from a domain that stopped Spanish expansion cold. Caddo confederacies farmed the east — their word for friend, táysha, named the province — while Apaches, Karankawas, and Wichitas held other regions. Spain planted missions and presidios, San Antonio from 1718, but Hispanic Texas stayed small: a few thousand Tejanos on a contested frontier."},
  {from:1821,to:1845,text:"Mexico, independent in 1821, admitted Anglo colonists under Stephen Austin; they brought cotton and slavery, defying Mexican abolition. Revolt came in 1835-36: the Alamo and Goliad fell, then Houston's army won San Jacinto. The Republic of Texas legalized slavery, expelled the Cherokee in 1839, and fought Comanches after the Council House betrayal of 1840. Annexation on December 29, 1845 made Texas the 28th state — and brought war with Mexico."},
  {from:1845,to:1875,text:"The US-Mexican War (1846-48) fixed the Rio Grande border. Cotton and enslaved labor spread; Texas seceded in 1861, deposing Governor Sam Houston. Emancipation reached Galveston on June 19, 1865 — Juneteenth. Frontier war continued until the 1874-75 Red River War, when the Army and the bison slaughter broke Comanche and Kiowa power; Quanah Parker's band surrendered to reservation life at Fort Sill."},
  {from:1875,to:1945,text:"Longhorn drives, then barbed wire and railroads, turned the plains to ranches and cotton to sharecropping; Jim Crow and anti-Mexican violence, including 1910s Ranger killings in the borderlands, hardened. The 1900 Galveston hurricane killed about 8,000 people — America's deadliest disaster. Spindletop's gusher on January 10, 1901 launched the oil age; the East Texas field followed in 1930, and wartime petrochemicals urbanized the Gulf Coast."},
  {from:1945,to:2026,text:"NASA's Mission Control came to Houston in the early 1960s; Kennedy was assassinated in Dallas in 1963. Booms, busts, and Permian Basin fracking made Texas the top oil, gas, and wind power, with an economy larger than most nations. Hispanic Texans became the largest population group in 2022. Austin tech, sprawling metros, border politics, hurricanes, and the 2021 grid failure define its scale and strains."}
 ],
 sources:["Texas State Historical Association","U.S. Census Bureau","National Archives"]},
"49":{origin:"Mexican Cession (1848) → Utah Territory 1850 → statehood 1896 (45th)",namedFor:"From the Ute people, whose name may mean 'people of the mountains'",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1847,text:"Ute bands ranged the mountains and traded horses; Shoshone held the north, Goshutes the west desert, Southern Paiutes the south, and Navajos the southeast. The Domínguez-Escalante expedition mapped the region for Spain in 1776; Mexican traders' Old Spanish Trail later carried a traffic in Paiute captives. Mexico still held the Great Basin when Brigham Young's Latter-day Saint vanguard entered the Salt Lake Valley in July 1847."},
  {from:1847,to:1869,text:"Latter-day Saint refugees built an irrigated Zion — hundreds of settlements on Native water and land. The Walker War (1853-54) and Black Hawk War (1865-72) followed; in 1863 US troops massacred hundreds of Northwestern Shoshone at Bear River, just over today's Idaho line. Federal suspicion brought the 1857-58 Utah War; Mormon militiamen massacred about 120 emigrants at Mountain Meadows in 1857. The transcontinental railroad's golden spike joined at Promontory Summit in May 1869."},
  {from:1869,to:1896,text:"The railroad ended isolation and brought non-Mormon miners; Park City silver and Bingham copper opened as Utes were forced onto the Uintah reservation. Federal law hammered polygamy — the Edmunds (1882) and Edmunds-Tucker (1887) Acts jailed men, seized church property, and disenfranchised — until the church's 1890 Manifesto renounced plural marriage. Statehood came on January 4, 1896, with women's suffrage restored in the constitution."},
  {from:1896,to:2026,text:"Bingham Canyon grew into one of Earth's largest open-pit copper mines; defense bases and downwind fallout from Nevada tests marked the Cold War. The 2002 Winter Olympics announced modern Utah: Silicon Slopes tech, ski wealth, and the nation's fastest-growing, youngest population, still roughly half Latter-day Saint. The Great Salt Lake hit record lows in 2022 — an ecological alarm — while tribal water and land claims continue."}
 ],
 sources:["Utah Historical Society","U.S. Census Bureau"]},
"50":{origin:"Disputed New Hampshire and New York grants → independent Vermont Republic 1777 → 14th state 1791, first added to the original 13",namedFor:"French 'vert mont' — green mountain",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1791,text:"Western Abenaki homelands like Missisquoi on Lake Champlain had been thinned by epidemics and war; many withdrew to Odanak in Quebec while others remained, unrecognized, for two centuries. New Hampshire and New York sold conflicting grants; Ethan Allen's Green Mountain Boys defied New York, and Vermont declared itself an independent republic in 1777, its constitution the first to ban adult slavery. It joined the Union in 1791 as the fourteenth state."},
  {from:1791,to:1900,text:"Hill farmers stripped the forests for potash and sheep — Merino mania in the 1820s-40s left Vermont largely deforested — then turned to dairy as young Vermonters drained west. Fiercely antislavery, the state sent a large share of its men to the Civil War. Barre granite and Proctor marble drew Italian, Scottish, and French Canadian stoneworkers; railroads carried butter, cheese, and stone to the cities."},
  {from:1900,to:1970,text:"Rural decline bred dark chapters: a 1931 eugenics law enabled sterilizations that targeted Abenaki families and the rural poor. The flood of 1927, Vermont's worst disaster, killed 84 and forced a road-building modernization. Ski resorts at Stowe and beyond, then the interstates, converted hill towns to tourism; IBM's Burlington-area plant (1957) became the largest private employer as dairy consolidated."},
  {from:1970,to:2026,text:"Back-to-the-landers and the Act 250 environmental law (1970) pushed politics leftward; Vermont pioneered civil unions in 2000 and legislative same-sex marriage in 2009. The state finally recognized four Abenaki bands in 2011-12. Ben and Jerry's, craft beer, and the nation's largest maple crop brand a rural economy strained by aging, housing costs, and floods — Irene in 2011, then 2023. Bernie Sanders made Burlington a political export."}
 ],
 sources:["Vermont Historical Society","U.S. Census Bureau"]},
"51":{origin:"First permanent English colony (Jamestown 1607) → independence 1776 → ratified Constitution 1788 (10th)",namedFor:"For Elizabeth I, the 'Virgin Queen,' named in 1584",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1788,text:"The Powhatan chiefdom had been broken a century before; treaty tribes like the Pamunkey and Mattaponi kept small reservations dating to the 1600s — among America's oldest. Tobacco and an enslaved population nearing forty percent made Virginia the largest, richest colony, and its gentry — Washington, Jefferson, Madison, Mason — led the Revolution through Yorktown (1781). Virginia ratified the Constitution tenth, in June 1788, after a close and consequential debate."},
  {from:1788,to:1861,text:"Virginians held the presidency for 32 of the republic's first 36 years. Soil exhaustion turned the state into the domestic slave trade's great exporter: Richmond's auction houses shipped enslaved people south by the hundred thousand. Gabriel's conspiracy (1800) and Nat Turner's rebellion (1831) brought harsher codes. John Brown raided Harpers Ferry in 1859; Virginia seceded in April 1861, and Richmond became the Confederate capital."},
  {from:1861,to:1902,text:"More Civil War battles tore Virginia than any other state, from Manassas to Appomattox (1865), and the northwestern counties split away as West Virginia in 1863. Emancipation freed roughly half a million Virginians. The biracial Readjuster coalition briefly governed in the early 1880s before conservative rollback; the 1902 constitution's poll taxes and literacy tests then collapsed Black — and many poor white — voter rolls for two generations."},
  {from:1902,to:1970,text:"Jim Crow ruled: the 1924 Racial Integrity Act wrote eugenics into law, and registrar Walter Plecker's 'paper genocide' erased Virginia Indians from state records. The Byrd machine answered Brown v. Board with Massive Resistance — Prince Edward County closed its public schools for five years. Wars built Hampton Roads' naval complex, the Pentagon (1943), and CIA headquarters at Langley. Loving v. Virginia (1967) struck down interracial marriage bans nationwide."},
  {from:1970,to:2026,text:"Federal spending made Northern Virginia rich — contractors, the Dulles tech corridor, and the world's densest concentration of data centers. Douglas Wilder won the governorship in 1989, the first elected Black governor in US history. The Pamunkey (2015-16) and six more tribes (2018) finally gained federal recognition. Richmond's Confederate monuments came down in 2020, and a diversifying, suburb-driven Virginia now swings elections it once locked."}
 ],
 sources:["Encyclopedia Virginia","Library of Congress","U.S. Census Bureau"]},
"53":{origin:"Oregon Country (US by 1846 treaty) → Oregon Territory 1848 → Washington Territory 1853 → statehood 1889",namedFor:"For George Washington — the only state named for a president",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1853,text:"Coast Salish peoples — Duwamish, Suquamish, Nisqually, Lummi, and many more — ran salmon economies around Puget Sound; Chinookans commanded the lower Columbia; Yakama, Spokane, and Colville peoples held the plateau; Makah whalers hunted from Neah Bay. Smallpox arrived with 1770s maritime traders, killing vast numbers before most Native people ever saw a colonist. Hudson's Bay Company's Fort Vancouver (1825) ran the fur trade; the 1846 treaty made the land American."},
  {from:1853,to:1889,text:"Washington Territory organized in 1853. Governor Isaac Stevens pushed through treaties in 1854-55 — tribes ceded millions of acres but reserved fishing at 'usual and accustomed grounds,' words that would echo. War followed on Puget Sound and the plateau; Nisqually leader Leschi was hanged in 1858 on disputed charges and exonerated in 2004. Railroads arrived in the 1880s; Tacoma and Seattle boomed and expelled their Chinese residents in 1885-86. Statehood came in November 1889."},
  {from:1889,to:1942,text:"The 1897 Klondike rush made Seattle the gateway to Alaska. Weyerhaeuser bought vast railroad land grants in 1900; timber and salmon canning ruled, and IWW organizing met violence at Everett (1916) and Centralia (1919) while Seattle's 1919 General Strike stopped the city. Boeing began building planes in 1916. Grand Coulee Dam, completed in 1942, electrified the Northwest — and helped destroy the upper Columbia salmon runs at Kettle Falls."},
  {from:1942,to:2026,text:"War remade the state: Boeing bombers, Japanese American incarceration beginning with Bainbridge Island, and secret Hanford, whose reactors bred the Nagasaki bomb's plutonium and left America's costliest nuclear cleanup. Tribal fish-ins won the 1974 Boldt decision — half the salmon catch belongs to treaty tribes. Mount St. Helens erupted May 18, 1980. Microsoft, arriving in 1979, and Amazon (1994) built a tech capital wrestling with housing costs while dams-versus-salmon battles continue."}
 ],
 sources:["Washington State Historical Society","HistoryLink","U.S. Census Bureau"]},
"54":{origin:"Virginia's trans-Allegheny counties → separated during the Civil War → statehood 1863 (35th)",namedFor:"Western counties of Virginia, itself named for Elizabeth I, the 'Virgin Queen'",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1861,text:"The Alleghenies were Shawnee, Cherokee, and Iroquois hunting country, with Mingo and Delaware towns along the Ohio; the Iroquois sold claims at Fort Stanwix (1768) without Shawnee consent, and Dunmore's War — Point Pleasant, 1774 — forced Shawnee cession. Scots-Irish and German settlers filled mountain valleys where plantation slavery stayed comparatively small, feeding grievances against tidewater rule over taxes, representation, and internal improvements."},
  {from:1861,to:1890,text:"When Virginia seceded, Unionist conventions at Wheeling formed a Restored Government and carved out a new state; Lincoln signed West Virginia into the Union on June 20, 1863, with gradual emancipation required by the Willey Amendment. Guerrilla war scarred the mountains. Afterward the Chesapeake and Ohio and Norfolk and Western railroads opened the southern coalfields, and land and mineral rights passed wholesale to absentee corporations — a defining dispossession."},
  {from:1890,to:1950,text:"Coal ruled through company towns, scrip, and mine guards; Black migrants, Italians, and Hungarians dug alongside mountaineers, and disasters recurred — Monongah (1907, 362 dead) remains America's worst mine disaster. The Mine Wars climaxed at Matewan (1920) and Blair Mountain (1921), where 10,000 armed miners fought until federal troops arrived — the largest US labor uprising. Hawks Nest Tunnel silicosis killed hundreds of mostly Black workers in the 1930s; loggers stripped the virgin forests."},
  {from:1950,to:2026,text:"Mechanization slashed mine jobs; population peaked in 1950 and fell for decades. The Buffalo Creek dam failure killed 125 in 1972; mountaintop-removal mining buried streams across the coalfields; Upper Big Branch killed 29 miners in 2010. The Kanawha chemical valley, opioids, and the nation's highest overdose death rates followed coal's collapse, while New River Gorge, a national park since 2020, anchors a growing outdoor economy."}
 ],
 sources:["West Virginia Archives and History","U.S. Census Bureau"]},
"55":{origin:"New France → British 1763 → US Northwest Territory 1787 → Wisconsin Territory 1836 → statehood 1848",namedFor:"From an Algonquian name for the Wisconsin River, recorded by Marquette as 'Meskousing' in 1673",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1832,text:"Ho-Chunk, Menominee, Ojibwe, Potawatomi, Sauk, and Meskwaki peoples wove fur-trade alliances with the French, then the British, from Green Bay and Prairie du Chien; Métis communities grew at the portages. After 1816 the US built forts, and eastern nations — Oneida, Stockbridge-Munsee, Brothertown — were relocated to Wisconsin. A southwestern lead-mining rush drew thousands of 'Badger' miners onto Ho-Chunk lands, forcing disputed cessions."},
  {from:1832,to:1900,text:"The 1832 Black Hawk War ended in massacre at Bad Axe as Sauk families fled across the Mississippi. Treaties took nearly everything: Ho-Chunk removals were repeatedly defied — families kept walking home; the Menominee kept a Wolf River homeland; Ojibwe treaties (1837, 1842) reserved hunting, fishing, and gathering rights. Statehood came in 1848 with German and Scandinavian waves. Lumbermen leveled the northern pineries; the 1871 Peshtigo Fire killed over 1,100 — America's deadliest."},
  {from:1900,to:1954,text:"Cutover farms failed; Wisconsin became America's Dairyland instead, built on university science, silos, and cheese cooperatives. La Follette's Progressives created the Wisconsin Idea: pioneering workers' compensation (1911), unemployment insurance (1932), and direct primaries. Milwaukee elected Socialist mayors for decades while breweries, Allis-Chalmers machinery, and Great Migration workers powered industry — and Senator McCarthy supplied the counterpoint. In 1954 Congress voted to terminate the Menominee Tribe."},
  {from:1954,to:2026,text:"Menominee termination proved disastrous; Ada Deer's campaign won restoration in 1973. Ojibwe treaty rights, affirmed in the 1983 Voigt decision, drew violent boat-landing protests before prevailing. Manufacturing declined; Act 10 (2011) gutted public-sector unions in Progressivism's birthplace. Dairy consolidates as small farms vanish, Milwaukee remains deeply segregated, and Wisconsin decides presidential elections by whiskers."}
 ],
 sources:["Wisconsin Historical Society","U.S. Census Bureau"]},
"56":{origin:"Louisiana Purchase plus Oregon Country and Mexican Cession fragments → Wyoming Territory 1868 → statehood 1890",namedFor:"From a Munsee Delaware word meaning 'at the big river flat,' borrowed from Pennsylvania's Wyoming Valley",
 eras:[
  {from:1750,to:1868,text:"Eastern Shoshone, Crow, Cheyenne, Arapaho, and later Lakota peoples hunted bison across the basins; Shoshone leader Washakie became a key US ally. Trappers' rendezvous met on the Green River (1825-40), and the Oregon, California, and Mormon trails funneled through South Pass. Red Cloud's War closed the Bozeman Trail forts; the 1868 treaties at Fort Laramie and Fort Bridger recognized Lakota hunting grounds and created the Wind River reservation."},
  {from:1868,to:1890,text:"The Union Pacific crossed southern Wyoming (1867-69), spawning Cheyenne, Laramie, and coal mines to feed it; in 1885 white miners massacred 28 Chinese coworkers at Rock Springs. The territory's first legislature granted women suffrage on December 10, 1869 — a world landmark. Yellowstone became the first national park in 1872, its tribes excluded. Northern Arapaho were placed on Wind River beside the Shoshone in 1878. Statehood came in 1890."},
  {from:1890,to:1970,text:"Cattle barons' power peaked in the 1892 Johnson County War, when hired gunmen invaded homesteader country. Salt Creek oil fed the Teapot Dome bribery scandal of the 1920s. Nellie Tayloe Ross became America's first woman governor in 1925, sealing the Equality State brand. Dude ranches and Grand Teton National Park grew tourism; during World War II some 14,000 Japanese Americans were incarcerated at Heart Mountain."},
  {from:1970,to:2026,text:"Powder River Basin strip mines made Wyoming the top US coal producer — roughly forty percent of national output at peak — alongside natural gas, trona, and uranium; mineral taxes fund the state. Matthew Shepard's 1998 murder near Laramie forced a national reckoning on anti-gay violence. Still the least populous state, at about 580,000 people, Wyoming balances coal's decline against Yellowstone-Teton tourism and Jackson's extreme wealth."}
 ],
 sources:["Wyoming State Archives","U.S. Census Bureau"]}
});
